The N, S-CQD-treated HuH-7 cell line showed a prominent fluorescence signal visualized through fluorescence microscopy (Fig. 5
                        ). This indicates that the water-soluble N, S-CQDs can readily penetrate within the mammalian cell. However, the successive treatment of the N, S-CQDs-treated HuH-7 cells with RIF resulted in the loss of their fluorescence properties. This observation indicated that in the in-vivo experiment when RIF get a chance to interact with the N, S-CQDs, the fluorescence “on” turns to “off” mode as found in the case of in vitro experiments. Furthermore, a similar observation was replicated using bacterial cells. The N, S-CQDs can efficiently label bacterial cells, as found under a fluorescence microscope (Fig. 6
                        ), while the same fluorescence gets abolished when the bacterial cells were treated with RIF.
